results.notes:
Growing on a slope with white pine, oak, hickory, and other hardwoods.

The cap color is pale for crenulata, and the uv deposits on the cap appear to be (nearly) white, although my camera perhaps failed to record enough yellow. There was frequent significant rainfall during this time; the one cap appears to be fairly well drenched. So, maybe this altered the appearance somewhat.

Spores subglose, broadly ellipsoid, and a few globose; ~7-9.2 × 6-9.

Photos labeled A, B represent separate collections made 20-30 feet apart.

results.notes:
Cap is streaked with pale tannish/greenish tinge against a pale ground color. Lots of rainfall likely washed out some of the pigment.
Mysterious to me how this type mushroom could suddenly appear in a spot on my property that has been scanned/examined for the past 17 years without ever seeing this species (until about one month ago). Trees in the immediate area are large white pine and shagbark hickory, each likely over 100 years old; mingling with other small trees; 10-20 foot tall oaks in the vicinity. There is one small spruce about 40 or so feet away (not sure how it got there), but this tree is only about 10 feet tall and unlikely to be a direct associate. Up until a couple years ago there had been a mature douglas fir on our property (planted), but ~100 feet away in the back yard.
Same location/habitat as obs 335930 (within 10 feet).

Additional details regarding habitat (including photos) may be found at obs 335930 . (This mushroom was found very close to where 335930 was found.)
